TI Anterior Cruciate Ligament Reconstruction with Semitendinosus Graft
   Provided Similar Stability and Knee Function and Fewer Problems with
   Kneeling Compared with the Bone-Patellar Tendon-Bone Graft
SO JOURNAL OF BONE AND JOINT SURGERY-AMERICAN VOLUME
LA English
DT Editorial Material
AB Question: In patients having an anterior cruciate ligament (ACL) reconstruction procedure, how do bone-patellar tendon-bone (BPTB) and semitendinosus (ST) grafts compare with regard to long-term knee function, graft-related morbidity, and health-related quality of life (HRQOL)?
   Design: Randomized (allocation concealed), unblinded, controlled trial with a mean follow-up of 8.4 years.
   Setting: 2 centers in Stockholm, Sweden.
   Patients: 164 patients (age range, fifteen to forty-five years) had a single-leg ACL insufficiency, with the trauma occurring at least two months before surgery, no previous ACL reconstruction in the involved knee, and no concomitant posterior cruciate ligament insufficiency. Of 180 patients randomized in the original trial with 2-year end points, 164 patients were included in this longer-term follow-up study; 153 patients (85%) (mean age, 34 years; 58% men) completed follow-up.
   Intervention: Patients were allocated to ACL reconstruction with use of an ipsilateral ST graft involving an EndoButton (Smith & Nephew, Andover, Massachusetts) on the femoral side and suture-over-post fixation on the tibia (n = 80) or antipsilateral BPTB graft involving interference screw fixation on the tibia and femoral sides (n = 84).
   Main outcome measures: Functional and knee-specific assessment included the Lysholm score; the Tegner activity level score; the International Knee Documentation Committee score; the patellofemoral pain score; a knee-walking test; a sensory loss question (patients were asked, "Do you experience a sensory loss?" [3-level response: no sensory loss, disturbed sensory loss, and lost sensitivity]); a 1-legged hop test; laxity measured by the Lachman test, the pivot-shift test, and maximum side-to-side difference as measured with use of a Rolimeter (MO, Coconut Creek, Florida); range of motion measured by deficits in extension and flexion; patient-rated knee function on 2 visual analog scales (score range 0 [worst] to 100 [best]) by answering 2 questions: "How does your knee function?" and "How does your knee affect your activity level?"; and HRQOL measured by scores on the Knee Osteoarthritis Outcome Score and the Short Form-36.
   Main results: At 8 years, between-group differences were observed in the kneeling subscore of the patellofemoral pain score, the knee-walking test, and sensory loss. More patients in the ST group than in the BPTB group reported no problem with kneeling (p < 0.001) and no problems in the knee-walking test (p < 0.001). Furthermore, patients in the ST group had less loss of skin sensation (p = 0.0019). The groups did not differ for any other outcomes.
   Conclusion: 8 years after ACL reconstruction, an ST graft was similar to a BPTB graft in stability, knee function, and health-related quality of life outcomes and resulted in fewer problems with kneeling and sensory loss.
