AU Gobbi, A
   Whyte, GP
AF Gobbi, Alberto
   Whyte, Graeme P.
TI Anatomic Double-Bundle and Single-Bundle ACL Reconstruction After ACL
   Rupture Did Not Differ for Quality of Life at 2 Years
SO JOURNAL OF BONE AND JOINT SURGERY-AMERICAN VOLUME
LA English
DT Editorial Material
AB Question: In patients with an anterior cruciate ligament (ACL) rupture, how do anatomic double-bundle (DB) and single-bundle (SB) ACL reconstruction compare for quality of life (QoL) at 2 years?
   Design: Randomized (allocation concealed), blinded (outcome assessors and statistical advisor; some patients), controlled trial with 2 years of follow-up. An inconsistency between the envelope allocations and the randomization list for 27% of patients was found when the randomization key was broken (ClinicalTrials.gov NCT01033188).
   Setting: 2 hospitals in Norway.
   Patients: 120 patients 18 to 40 years of age (mean age, 27 years; 76% men) who had an ACL rupture and had completed 2 months of knee-specific rehabilitation that was supervised by a physical therapist. Exclusion criteria included a partially ruptured ACL; injury of the posterior cruciate ligament, the lateral collateral ligament, or the posterolateral corner; medial collateral ligament injury with increased medial ligament laxity at surgery; knee osteoarthritis; previous ACL reconstruction in either knee; or insufficient graft thickness of the hamstring tendons after preparation. 94% of patients received the intervention and completed follow-up.
   Intervention: Patients were allocated toDB(n= 58) or SB (n = 62) ACL reconstruction. In the DB group, an accessory anteromedial (AM) portal was used to drill a femoral tunnel, and then a DB femoral drill guide was used to drill a posterolateral (PL) tunnel. On the tibial side, an external tibial guide was used to mark the center of the AM bundle footprint, the AM tunnel was pinned, the PL guide pin was placed in the footprint center, and the PL tunnel was drilled. Grafts were passed through the tibial and then femoral tunnels and were cycled through 20 flexion-extension movements. Fixation was performed under manual tension for the AM (60 degrees of flexion) and PL (full extension) bundles. Grafts were fixated on the femoral (2 suspension devices) and tibial (2 eccentrically placed PEEK [polyetheretherketone] interference screws) sides, ideally with minimum diameters of 6.0 mm for the AM bundle and 5.0 mm for the PL bundle. The technique for the SB group was similar to that of the DB group but without the PL tunnels and fixation; fixation on the tibial side was performed under manual tension with the knee at 20 degrees of flexion, and a suspension device was used for fixation on the femoral side.
   Main outcome measures: The primary outcome was the Knee injury and Osteoarthritis Outcome Score (KOOS) QoL subscore at 2 years. Secondary outcomes included the KOOS Pain, Symptoms, Activities of Daily Living, and Sports/Recreation subscores at 2 years. 112 patients provided 80% power to detect an 8-point difference in the KOOS QoL subscores (assuming a 15-point standard deviation, alpha = 0.05).
   Main results: The main results are listed in Table I.
   Conclusion: In patients with an ACL rupture, anatomic DB and SB ACL reconstruction did not differ for QoL at 2 years.
